    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>How Reliable Are Eyewitnesses?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Douglas G Mook letter says 'age-old' faith in jurors looking witness in the eye and determining the truth has been shown time and again to be utterly false</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Representative Asa Hutchinson writes (Op-Ed, June 22), ''America must not retreat from the age-old notion that 12 jurors can look a witness in the eye and, after hearing contradictory evidence, appropriately weigh his or her credibility.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Representative Asa Hutchinson writes (Op-Ed, June 22), ''America must not retreat from the age-old notion that 12 jurors can look a witness in the eye and, after hearing contradictory evidence, appropriately weigh his or her credibility.''</p>
        <p>Why shouldn't we retreat from that notion? It has been shown time and again to be utterly false.</p>
        <p>DOUGLAS G. MOOK  Astoria, Queens, June 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
